      "id": 1,
      "text": "Englewood Cliffs became a borough on May 10, 1895, carved out of Englewood Township and Palisades Township.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        20
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.njtgo.com/towns/E/Englewood%20Cliffs/Englewood_Cliffs.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The borough’s name honors the Engle family, who settled the area in 1859.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Englewood%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Erie Railroad’s Northern Branch began passenger service in Englewood in 1859, with a still‑standing depot at Depot Square.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Englewood%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Congregation Ahavath Torah, a Modern Orthodox synagogue, was founded in 1895 and moved to its current site in 1958.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Englewood%2C_New_Jersey"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "From 1906 to 1907, Englewood hosted Upton Sinclair’s Helicon Home Colony, a brief socialist‑inflected intentional community.",
